 Twitter (https://twitter.com/caseynewton), if you miss me.=C2=A0

Today's big story is that a lie gets halfway around the world before the tr=
uth can put its shoes on. That quote is usually attributed to Mark Twain, b=
ut it's also a lie =E2=80=94 one that has been circling the globe since abo=
ut 1919 (https://quoteinvestigator.com/2014/07/13/truth/). Whatever the pro=
venance of the quote, it has new data to support it. Here's my colleague An=
gela Chen in=C2=A0The Verge (https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/8/17096538/fak=
e-news-twitter-information-social-media)=C2=A0on an important new study:

In a paper published today in the journal Science, researchers analyzed the=
 spread of all the stories verified (as either true or false) by six fact-c=
hecking organizations from 2006 to 2017. The analysis shows that false poli=
tical news spreads more quickly than any other kind, like news about natura=
l disasters or terrorism, and predictably, it spikes during events like the=
 2012 and 2016 US presidential elections. (The researchers deliberately use=
 the term =E2=80=9Cfalse news=E2=80=9D because =E2=80=9Cfake news=E2=80=9D =
is too politicized, they write.) Though the Twitter accounts that spread un=
truthful stories were likely to have fewer followers and tweet less than th=
ose sharing real news, false news still spreads quickly because it is seen =
as novel, the study says.First, the researchers went to six fact-checking o=
rganizations and pulled out all the news stories they had verified as true =
or false. (The six orgs were Snopes, PolitiFact, FactCheck, Truth or Fictio=
n, Hoax Slayer, and Urban Legends.) Next, the researchers =E2=80=94 who had=
 access to the entire Twitter archive =E2=80=94 looked for mentions of thes=
e stories on the social media site. Each time they found a mention, they wo=
uld try to determine whether that mention was the original tweet, or if it =
was replying to or repeating a different tweet. That way, they could trace =
the origin of the story, and then track the ways that the information sprea=
d through Twitter. Ultimately, their dataset included about 126,000 stories=
 tweeted by 3 million people more than 4.5 million times.Their analysis sho=
ws that true news rarely spread to more than 1,000 people, but the top 1 pe=
rcent of false news could spread to as many as 100,000. This wasn=E2=80=99t=
 because the accounts tweeting false news were particularly influential, bu=
t because we=E2=80=99re more likely to share news that seems interesting an=
d new. =E2=80=9CNovel information is thought to be more valuable than redun=
dant information,=E2=80=9D says study co-author Sinan Aral, a professor of =
management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. =E2=80=9CPeople wh=
o spread novel information gain social status because they=E2=80=99re thoug=
ht to be =E2=80=98in the know=E2=80=99 or to have inside information.=E2=80=
=9DOver at Vox, Brian Resnick takes an in-depth look at how novelty drives =
so much social-media sharing =E2=80=94 and how fake news capitalizes on tha=
t fact (https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2018/3/8/17085928/fake-news-=
study-mit-science):

=E2=80=9CFalse news was significantly more novel than true news,=E2=80=9D A=
ral says. =E2=80=9CAnd that makes sense =E2=80=94 when you are unconstraine=
d by reality, you can come up with much more novel information.=E2=80=9D A =
sentiment analysis in the Science paper revealed that replies to false news=
 tweets contained more expressions of surprise or disgust than true news. A=
nd perhaps that=E2=80=99s why fake celebrity deaths so often pervade Twitte=
r: They=E2=80=99re surprising, emotional, irresistible to share.And this =
=E2=80=9Cnovelty=E2=80=9D hypothesis has been shown in other studies. In a =
2017 paper that Rand co-authored, when participants see headlines repeated,=
 they=E2=80=99re more likely to believe them (a consequence of what=E2=80=
=99s known as the illusory truth effect), but less likely to share them on =
social media. Other research has found that the more morally or emotionally=
 charged a tweet, the more likely it is to spread within a particular ideol=
ogical group.Where does that leave us? Aside from a few bromides to &quot;t=
hink before you share,&quot; I'm not really sure. I hardly know a reporter=
=C2=A0who hasn't shared something on Twitter they found out later not to be=
 true, much less an average citizen. This is one reason why Farhad Manjoo a=
rgued yesterday that we should just wait for the next day's paper to come o=
ut (https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/07/technology/two-months-news-newspaper=
s.html), though I suspect that few who read this newsletter will feel as if=
 they have that luxury.

In the Atlantic, Robinson Meyer speaks for the crowd (https://www.theatlant=
ic.com/technology/archive/2018/03/largest-study-ever-fake-news-mit-twitter/=
555104/):

In short, social media seems to systematically amplify falsehood at the exp=
ense of the truth, and no one=E2=80=94neither experts nor politicians nor t=
ech companies=E2=80=94knows how to reverse that trend. It is a dangerous mo=
ment for any system of government premised on a common public reality.=C2=
